In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a high score of A.
Data collected from a total of 74 SCIS schools show that 72 percent of students received a grade of A in Mandarin, 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners.
This shows that Scottish private schools support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages, which are now among the subject choices, are included in the curricula of private schools and other schools in the same way as STEM subjects (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics).
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills revealed that among the reasons why employers find it difficult to find jobs, 17% of respondents reported lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly mandatory to prepare young people for their future jobs.
As more hopeful job offers require language skills, such skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career choice you make, learning a second language will give you a real advantage in the future, as language skills will be lifelong.
The ability to communicate directly with foreign citizens immediately gives a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents do not speak any foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation. The only language with a two-digit percentage of speakers was French with 15 percent.
Therefore, funding for language learning is important for today’s children.
Knowing several languages, especially those of emerging economies, gives children better opportunities to find a good job.
Different languages are taught in every school in Scotland.
A number of schools prefer to focus on classical modern languages, while other schools teach languages that are considered the most important in the UK for 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of the child, private schools always have the option of choosing between several languages, which are taught by experts in their field.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
It can no longer be denied that in a globalised business environment, languages are crucial for the future of a country, and therefore must be reflected in education.
It is modern languages that should be considered as “international communication skills”.
Private schools continue to offer young Scots choice, diversity and excellence.
Il faut bien le faire.
