Harvard Students Learn How to Get Enough Rest
This year, Harvard University offers a new course where students need to sleep more to fight the growing aggressive culture of learning through caffeinated night-to-day learning marathons.
Students who love academia at the world’s best university are often helpless when it comes to the basics of taking care of themselves.
This course was designed by Harvard Medical School anaesthetist and Brigham and Women's Hospital expert Professor Charles Czeisler, who said it was the first of its kind in the United States.
She was inspired to create a course after giving a speech on how sleep disorders affect learning.
“At the end of it, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I being told about this only now, in my last year of school?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - it made me nervous," she told the Telegraph.
The course, which entered the curriculum for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic outcomes and also help to improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of health care at the university, said the university decided to take a course of study after finding that students were severely sleep-deprived during their working week.
The one-hour course covers a number of interactional tasks.
In one section, students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books, and learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how sleep deprivation affects their athletic performance and the importance of sleeping habits.
The second part explains to participants how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with reciprocal symbols encourages participants to think about their daily practice.
“We know that this does not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know about the health effects of smoking cigarettes," Professor Czeisler said.
He said that there is still pride in study marathons at night, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation is still a growing problem.
“Providing adequate quality sleep should be a student’s ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, exhaustion, and anxiety,” he added. “It even helps with weight gain, as lack of sleep puts the brain in a hunger state, making a person constantly hungry.”
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and physical biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his classes in his first Harvard year.
Raymond said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to contribute to the creation of an inter-university course.
As a next step, he wants all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining a competing institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set alarm clocks for both sleeping and waking, and to be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” caused by electronic displays and LED lighting, as this could damage their daily rhythm and cause problems with sleep.
